                    <item>
              <title>Presentation: Goodyear, Kali &amp; Tickner Complex spaces for learning: theory and practice in design, co-design and re-design</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2762</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2762</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Complex spaces for learning: theory and practice in design, co-design and re-design</strong></p>
<p><em>Peter Goodyear, Yael Kali and Sue Tickner</em></p>
<p>Plan is to produce a report out of the event, want people to feel free to be frank.</p>
<p><em>Peter Goodyear</em></p>
<p>A central challenge that emerges from the changing landscape is about working out how we can make pedagogical sense of these changes. Can we view design as a means of managing this change, what would this look like? Spaces for learning &ndash; physical, virtual are becoming more complex. Couple that with a notion that students will and should be more actively involved in reconfiguring their own learning.</p>
<ul>
<li>Experience of co-design with students and also re-design</li>
<li>Design as imaging other people&rsquo;s learning</li>
<li>Activity distributed in complex ways across time, space, tools and people</li>
<li>Students and teacher co-configuring activity relationships and learnplaces</li>
<li>Extended concept of self-regulation: activity relationships and tools/resources</li>
</ul>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Lassez-faire&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;&hellip;Instructional design</p>
<p>[loose vs. tight structures]</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Not just about managing activities but the social interactions., also how to make good choices about tools and resources.</p>
<p>Is design too complicated &ndash; should we just let students get on with it??? Some argue from the position of students as experts anyway, aligning with Prensky&rsquo;s notions, whereas now most don&rsquo;t subscribe to that position. In reality students&rsquo; digital habits are very varied, they may not know how to use these technologies for learning</p>
<p>Alternative approach to help students find their way through this space, need classic application of instructional design and more rigour, discipline, etc.</p>
<p>In reality it&rsquo;s probably somewhere in between.</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p><strong>Teaching as design</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Diversifying student needs and expectations</li>
<li>Rising expectations abut graduate capabilities</li>
<li>Intensification of pressures on teaching staff</li>
<li>Accelerating technological change</li>
</ul>
<p>Increasing stress on traditional teaching processes</p>
<p>Accumulating research evidence about learning and teaching</p>
<p>Activity-centred design &ndash; design cannot be content focussed, must be on what the student does. It&rsquo;s the alignment between the desired learning outcomes and the activities we want the students to engage with. A key element of the design challenge is designing the student tasks. Of course students will interpret what we ask them to do (for good or bad). There is a gap between the tasks we set and the activities the students do.</p>
<p>We must remember that learning is physically situated &ndash; there are multiple learnplaces and this is fundamentally important and shapes the quality of the activities the students do.</p>
<p>Also learning is socially situated, groups, teams and communities + virtual teams, groups, and communities</p>
<p>Accelerating interpenetration of the digital and material worlds</p>
<p>Ubiquitous computing/ambient intelligence</p>
<p>Rise and rise of personal technologies</p>
<p><strong>Three inter-related components</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Outcomes</li>
<li>Activity &ndash; place is a part of this, as is community. We must remember we don&rsquo;t control these spaces </li>
<li>Task</li>
</ul>
<p>We also need to think about scale &ndash; macro, meso and micro. For each we can think about tasks, tools and people. A lot of what we do as teachers is at the meso level. Design of a single task, mapped to a single coherent activity. Timeframe days or weeks. The set of tools, spaces and other resource needed for the learners works on a specific activity. Usually the concern of a teacher or programme team, may be co-configured by the learner(s). People: arrangement into working groups that persist for the length of the activity.</p>
<p>Teaching as design is indirect because of</p>
<ul>
<li>The legitimate and unavoidable gap between tasks and activity</li>
<li>Co-configuration of the complex mix</li>
<li>Autonomy exercised by students in making choice about who to work with and how but needs careful scaffolding</li>
<li>Plus alignment up and down the system macro &ndash; to micro-</li>
<li>Against this can we support teachers design work?</li>
</ul>
<p><em>Sue Tickner</em></p>
<p>Imaging learning: enabling design</p>
<p>Design/learning</p>
<p>Action (Revised design) &ndash; feedback &ndash; opportunity to respond (feed forward)</p>
<p>Dialogic process to reach a mutual understanding &ndash; when design is collaborative there are more opportunities for feedback and so learning</p>
<p>Levels of collaborative design?</p>
<ol>
<li>Reacting to feedback on existing design &ndash; adaptive</li>
<li>Designing for student contributions to and flexible use of environment we provide tools and resources and opportunities</li>
<li>Handing over (parts of) the design to the learners</li>
</ol>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<ol>
<li>On the fly, rapid changes according to feedback. In the moment imaging the immediate learning needs, they need new space for this, just in time, highly responsive contextual, at extreme, similar to formative testing, rapid prototyping, labs observation, on going support. Examples &ndash; one-click surveys within a course, watching their intros in labs, group discussions need to come back together, add a new whole class one. Also process &ndash; design stems from philosophy and values, reflected in methods, the &lsquo;teachable moment&rsquo;</li>
<li>Negotiated marking criteria/assessment rubrics. Co-constructed bibliographies and resource banks. Evaluation criteria for group processes. Spaces for students to create/share their own resources. Examples role play scenarios, resource bank wiki. Educ 230 Wikis, blogs, negotiated assessment criteria, self-assessment, group process critique. Self and peer assessment, criteria and review. Orientation course &ndash; chat, RSS feeds, practice wikis. Self, group, lecturer-reflection. As locus of control shifts during the shared assessment process, there is also a greater appreciation that all learners are teachers and teachers continue to be learners.</li>
<li>Students co-construct teaching resources in groups using whatever of the available technologies/resources they choose. Then create teaching spaces and co-teach. Students create resource banks and presentations to share. TLT group smart classrooms. Communication and making connections, sharing resources, encourage learners to interact spontaneously. Wheatley and Frieze *2006 using emergence to take social innovation to scale </li>
</ol>
<p><em>Yael Kali</em></p>
<p><strong>Redesign as a strategy to create, refine and share design knowledge gained in an iterative design process</strong></p>
<p>Approach to design &ndash; methodological approach &ndash; design-based research and strategic approach the use of the design principles and the design principles database (DPD)</p>
<p>Methodological approach &ndash; Barab and Squire 2004, Collins, Joseph and Bielaczyc 2004, The design-based research collective 2003</p>
<ul>
<li>Iteration 1</li>
<li>Iteration 2 Enactment of the revised version of the features, data gathering, data analysis and conclusions</li>
<li>Iteration 3</li>
</ul>
<p>Design Principles Database</p>
<p>Edu-design-principles.org Create an infrastructure for the community of educational technology designers and learning scientists to capture synthesise and discuss design knowledge</p>
<p>Structure is hierarchical have over 100 examples. Features then pragmatic principles (general guidelines about design, but also connected to learning theory) and then meta-principles</p>
<p>Example: web-based jigsaw activity: philosophical perspectives</p>
<p>Specialization groups in online discussions (progressivism, existentialism, essentialism), the knowledge sharing in home groups, then individual application of the knowledge in a new context (using perspective to analyse a school)</p>
<p>DP1: engage learners in peer instruction. Rationale &ndash; taking the role of instructor can encourage sutdents to depend understaning of content, increase motivation etc Topping 1996 Linn and His 2000 But trade off main contribution to those who instruct and less to those who learn</p>
<p>DP2: reuse students artefacts as resource for further learning</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>
<p>Iteration 1 &ndash; First version was unstructured discussion, found very low application of the knowledge in a new context, Students focussed on the perspective they had specialised in.</p>
<p>Iteration 2: Provided them with a tool. Collaboratively constructed table as attachment in the forum. Found application of knowledge was even lower!!!</p>
<p>Iteration 3: Used the same table, but this time students didn&rsquo;t download, it was in a wiki format. This made a big difference, because when they completed their rows they could see what others had contributed and could compare and contrast. Also enabled them to edit each others&rsquo; contributions. So a better application of DP3 and DP4</p>
<p>DP3: provide knowledge representation and organisation tools</p>
<p>DP4: Employ multiple social activity structures</p>
<p>Lessons learned &ndash; redesign as a strategy to create, refine and share design knowledge gained in an iterative design process. Design based research approach provides insights about the use of technology to apply design principles</p>
<p>Design knowledge gained in this process can become part of the design principles (tips: tradeoffs, pitfalls, limitations)</p>
<p>Comments on the presentation</p>
<ul>
<li>Small tweaks in redesign can have a huge impact on the success of the activity.</li>
<li>Interesting that between iteration 2 and 3 the major change was in the tool rather than the tasks.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Learners can be initially quite reluctant to edit their co-learners contributions, need to encourage and support that</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Discussion</strong></p>
<p>What do you do when people don&rsquo;t agree about the edits in the wiki, one delegate has a forum alongside the wiki so there can be a negotiation about how the wiki is edited</p>
<p><em>Issues </em></p>
<p>Co-design: Think about situations where you have handed over to the students, so there is considerable autonomy given over to the students. Think around tasks, tools, or how they work with others. Wants us to concentrate on the latter two rather than tasks.</p>
<p>Examples</p>
<ul>
<li>One example with masters&rsquo; students. Give flexibility to choose their research questions and focus and which databases to use, but they wanted to be guided more.</li>
<li>Cancelled all lectures once and told students to go and look at the materials online.</li>
<li>Students working in a global context and had to negotiate a project. They all abandoned the learner management space and took their discussion to a private space.</li>
<li>P/g e-learning course, last year moved to more flexible approach, allowed them to take over certain parts of the course and they choose the tools they wanted to use and moderated the space.</li>
<li>Put students into a public social networking site and asked them to share they professional practice and some interesting debates occurred in the communities.</li>
<li>Another example got the students to write a chapter around their subject area.</li>
</ul>
<p>Re-design: Has anyone got examples they can share of good re-designs? It's not just about re-designs which are based on solid data but also scholarly practice - teachers often have a natural, intuitive understanding of what works and what doesn't. Iterative re-design is surely an inherent part of teacher practice.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Tue, 08 Dec 2009 01:40:05 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>What is a Design Atelier? </title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2715</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2715</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>Prompted by an interesting discussion at a JISC Cluster Meeting I have created this cloud to explore further what a Design Atelier actually is?&nbsp;<br /><br /><strong>Background<br /></strong>The <a href="http://www.jisc.ac.uk/whatwedo/programmes/elearning/curriculumdelivery/atelierd.aspx">ATELIER-D</a> project takes as its starting point the centuries-old methods of learning and teaching in the studio of a master artist or craftsperson. The project brings the spirit of the atelier into the 21st century. It develops the notion of the &lsquo;virtual design studio&rsquo; using ICTs to create powerful learning and teaching environments.</p>
<p>&nbsp;In his keynote presentation at the OpenLearn conference&nbsp;30-31st October 2007 at The Open University (OU), John Seeley Brown used the term &lsquo;atelier&rsquo; to characterise an emerging form of learning and teaching based on social networks, a distinct participatory approach by learners and teachers and pedagogy rooted in practice. Seeley Brown drew on his experience in architecture education but many in the parent domain of design education will recognise the well-established and powerful approach offered by the atelier (see link below).<br /><br />As part of the JISC funded ATELIER-D project the OU are researching how a virtual atelier can be created using the latest Web 2.0 tools that support a wide range of distance learning designs students.<br /><strong><br />This cloud<br /></strong>This cloud seeks to promote discussion about what you think a Design Atelier is?</p>
<ul>
<li>What are the key attributes that make up a Design Atelier?&nbsp;&nbsp;</li>
<li>What makes it so special?</li>
<li>Is the nature of the physical space important?&nbsp; Should it be large and open or small&nbsp; and private?</li>
<li>What type of teaching methods should be used?</li>
<li>How can communication be used to support learning?&nbsp;</li>
</ul>
<p>This link&nbsp;below takes&nbsp;you to a short video clip to prompt the discussion. <br />Your thoughts and views are most welcome.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Fri, 27 Nov 2009 17:41:28 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Design problem, design solution</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2651</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2651</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>Survey</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Survey looking at staff perceptions around learning design in the OU</li>
<li>It is becoming harder to understand how all the parts of planned learning and teaching fit together. Ca. 60% agree this is true</li>
<li>The advent of e-learning is making the process of creating courses more complex. Over 70% agree</li>
<li>Technologies available today offer great potential for enhancing student learning experience. Ca 80%</li>
<li>Technologies will deliver great enhancements in student learning experience. Less than the above, i.e. confidence in it making a different is less</li>
<li>Do you believe that more use of visual representation could help students better understand and plan their study. Over 70% agree</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Process/product&hellip; design solution</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>It&rsquo;s about the process of problem solving, with the product being more about analysis, evaluation and sharing. A lot of the representations are of the design solution. Would like to explore more how we represent the problem</li>
<li>Lee and Nelson, 2005 Many studies have been conducted to investigate influential factors on problem-solving performance and relevant approaches that support successful problem solving. &hellip; importance of knowledge representation that is a solvers knowledge and the structure.</li>
<li>There have been a number of attempts to represent at the task level &ndash; such as the AUTC swimlines of resources, tasks and support. The CompendiumLD task swimline representations as well. </li>
<li>Have been working with a course team T100 at the draft stage of course development. Once the course has been drafted then often it goes out for developmental testing. And finally looking at a course in production. </li>
<li>Using Cmap as a means of mapping this. Interested in using this to map at the block level. At the top have prior knowledge and skills and at the bottom is where you want the students to end up in terms of learning outcome. Mapping learning and understanding to what students actually do. </li>
<li>Enables you to see the dependencies between different components. </li>
<li>Moving away from the sequential temporal task sequences. </li>
<li>Have an activity that enables people to see the value of representing things visual. Takes a week of learning from our H808 course.</li>
<li>An interesting activity is to look at a visual representation of this and then consider whether or not the learning outcmes had been met and how long will the activity take.</li>
</ul>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Thu, 12 Nov 2009 10:31:28 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Keynote: Goodyear - &#39;Learning through Inquiry and Teaching-as-design&#39; </title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2578</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2578</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p><strong>From the AECT website: </strong></p>
<p><strong>Description:</strong>&nbsp;&nbsp;                                     His presentation will start by summarising outcomes from recent research on how university students approach complex inquiry-based learning tasks that involve significant use of educational technology. The research reveals significant variations in how students make sense of such challenges, how they negotiate between their own and their teachers&rsquo; goals, and how environmental factors influence the nature and outcomes of their learning activity. The discussion will focus on some of the ways in which students&rsquo; conceptions of learning, and other beliefs about learning, interact with their technological choices and with their use (or non-use) of the various kinds of support that their teachers provide. This picture of students exercising autonomy in their learning, but making choices that are not always optimal, will then be used as a backdrop for explaining a conception of university teaching called &lsquo;teaching-as-design&rsquo;. Peter will sketch a model of teaching-as-design and then focus on forms of knowledge and ways of knowing that stand a reasonable chance of improving teachers&rsquo; educational design activity. Finally, he will draw out some implications for an educational technology research agenda that is fit for the purpose of improving the integrative challenges of teaching-as-design.</p>
<p>Professor of education and co-director of the CoCo Research Centre, University of Sydney, Senior Fellow, Australian Learning and Teaching Council</p>
<p><strong>Three parts to the keynote</strong></p>
<ol>
<li>Research into students experience of learning in blended learning contexts</li>
<li>Concept of teaching as design</li>
<li>Forms of knowledge capture, ways of sharing expertise for design between teachers involved in designing for students</li>
</ol>
<p><strong>1. Learning through inquiry</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Inquiry learning is about - all forms of educational activity that give a central place to students ingvetigattive work. For example problem-based learning,&nbsp; project-based learning, or&nbsp; collaborative knowledge building</li>
<li>It may be Individual&nbsp; or group based, and often involves discussion for coordinated as well as knowledge building</li>
<li>Draws on: 
<ul>
<li>Important in terms of development of graduate capabilities &ndash; Argyris, C (1998) "Teaching smart people how to learn" &ndash; Harvard Bus Review on Knowledge Management, Cam MA</li>
<li>Boulton G and Lucas C 2008 "What are universities for?" <a href="http://www.leru.org/">www.leru.org</a></li>
</ul>
</li>
<li>Learning to deal with complexity, helping students to deal with this</li>
<li>Goodyear and Zenios 2007 BJET 55 (4) discussion collaborative knowledge work and epistemic fluency</li>
<li>Researching university students experiences of blended learning from a phenomenographic perspective 0 students conceptions of learning, students approaches to study &ndash; strategies and intentions.Undertook a set of In depth interviews n = 20, open ended survey n = 50 and likert scale instruments n =100</li>
<li>New book Ellis and Goodyear Routledge, 2009</li>
<li>Taped and transcribed &ndash; each read independently by 3 researchers &ndash; illuminating phrases and main themes noted and compared, further reading, categories, comparison, discussion, final agreement</li>
<li>Three areas: conceptions, f2f approaches, online approaches</li>
<li>Adv in Health Sci Educ (2008) 13: 675-692</li>
<li>Concepts of PBL a way if developing independent clinical reasoning and problem solving abilities through to more restricted views as a way of covering topics to answer problems, a way of followig a predefined process. Get a lot of variation between the students in terms of what they think they can get out of PBL</li>
<li>Approaches &ndash; deep vs. surface. Find that very few of the students are actually adopting deep learning approaches</li>
<li>Distribution of conceptions and approaches &ndash; the majority are not adopting richer notions of PBL or deep approaches, there is a mis-match between the teachers intentions and what they students are actually doing. Translates through to end of course grades</li>
<li>Students should make choices in HE need to become autonomous, about how they respond to the tasks set for them, what tools and resource to use</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>But their choices are less than optimal. The patterns we see are familiar from 30 years of HE research, but we are picking it up in contexts where technology plays a role too.</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>Students are looking to us &ndash; their teachers for guidance&rsquo;s even about the educational use of technologies</li>
</ul>
<ul>
<li>What form should design guidance&rsquo;s take when it needs tow ork in participatory/co-design/co-configuration context?</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>2. Teaching as design</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>The decline of the compliant learner &ndash; in HE there isn&rsquo;t a systematic approach to instructional design/learning design. The challenges teachers are facing now are incredibly complex, to try and help students benefit from the opportunities need a more systematic approach need to use some design tools. Some of ideas of instructional design have assumed a compliant learner &ndash; they will do what they are set. This is not true in HE and we don&rsquo;t want them to be compliant. We want them to be creative, to interpret the task, to appropriate it. Design more about the crafting of affordances than the determination of activities.</li>
<li>The architecture of productive learning environments</li>
<li>Educational design as the crafting of affordances</li>
<li><em>From sage on the stage to guide on the side</em></li>
<li>Teaching as telling towards teaching as facilitation</li>
<li>Learning by listening to learning by doing (more activity-based learning)</li>
<li>But we also need to include &ndash; teaching as design&hellip; <em>ie to the team with a scheme</em></li>
<li>C21 learning is different and we need to adapt our design methods to better reflect this&ndash; learning to think for a living, teacher-researcher, extended professional</li>
<li>Multiple intended learning outcomes tasks &ndash; lead to activity &ndash; leads to outcomes</li>
<li>Distinction between task (what the teacher sets for the student to do) and activity (what the students actually do)</li>
<li>Legitimate (re)interpretation of task: creative, personalised, &ldquo;satisficing&rdquo;</li>
<li>Learning is physically situated &ndash; &ldquo;learnplaces&rdquo; and is socially situated &ndash; groups, teams and communities</li>
<li>Then design centred on student activities &ndash; people, community and tools, resource and infrastructure, social relations, place. With the tasks as the &ldquo;rules&rdquo;</li>
<li>Indirect approach to design &ndash; learnplace, social space and tasks</li>
<li>We need to design these design components (task, tools, people) from the micro, meso and macro level. We need to better integrate across these as well.</li>
<li>Teaching as design &ndash; indirect because legitimised by the students gap bet task specified and subsequent student activities</li>
<li>Co-configuration of the complex mix of material and digital tools, resources and places</li>
<li>Autonomy exercised by students in making choices about who to work with and how</li>
<li>Plus alignment up and down the system &ndash; macro to micro</li>
<li>Against this backdrop how can we support teachers&rsquo; design work?</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>3. Capturing and sharing experiential and evidence based knowledge for design</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Goodyear and Retalis, forthcoming edited collection on current research on pedagogical patterns. &ldquo;Technology-enhanced learning design patterns and patterns languages&rdquo;</li>
<li>A pattern is a solution to a recurrent problem in a context Alexander et al., 1977</li>
<li>A pattern describes a problem which occurs over and over again in our environment and then describes the core of the solution to that problem, in such a way that you can use this solution a millions times over</li>
<li>Structure: context, essence of the problem, rationale, the solution (which is action orientated), smaller patterns</li>
</ul>
<p><strong><em>Pedagogical pattern: Umpire</em></strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Defines a role that is useful in a umber of group task patterns</li>
<li>Lively discussion can generate emotion and someone will occasionally say something offensive&hellip;</li>
<li>Solution make it responsibility o the group to deal with offensive comments, give one or two students the role of umpire</li>
<li>Lower level patterns &ndash; scribe and wrapper and whistle</li>
<li>These fit together in a pattern language</li>
<li>Course, inquiry task, planning group _ problem scenario, umpire + scribe + wrapper</li>
</ul>
<p><strong><em>Design patterns and pattern languages: take home points</em></strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Design as intimately involved in balancing competing forces</li>
<li>Contextualised guidance vs. universal principles</li>
<li>Linking rationale to action-oriented guidance including students</li>
<li>Rationale can draw on experience theory empirical data etc</li>
<li>Performance support balance with professional development</li>
<li>Giving names to useful recurrent forms is a significant contribution (for example the jigsaw pattern)</li>
<li>Linking design patterns to software etc</li>
</ul>
<p><strong><em>Conclusion</em></strong></p>
<p>Students are active interpreters of task requirements</p>
<p>Educational designs need to have ways of helping us talk abut design of good tasks</p>
<p>In relation to tasks, tools and people, students will need to exercise significant autonomy in their choices, often make sub-optimal choices, there are things we can do to help with this, better scaffolding, changing the culture</p>
<p>Major practical challenge &ndash; managing the interface between increasing smart and ubiquitous technologies and the local infrastructure</p>
<p>Transforming knowledge so that its application by time poor undertrained teachers and in local contexts</p>
<p>Having a shared sense of the architecture of what we are trying to create can really focus outputs from research in educational technology/learning sciences &ndash; a clearer sense of the users of research and the specifics of their needs</p>
<p>&nbsp;</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Fri, 30 Oct 2009 12:34:49 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
                    <item>
              <title>Journal article: Cog-learn</title>
              <link>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2467</link>
              <guid>https://cloudworks.ac.uk/cloud/view/2467</guid>
              <description><![CDATA[<p>This article describes the cog-learn tool, along with some case studies of its use.</p>
<p>From the article<br />Cog-Learn is a pattern language aimed at supporting the design of learning material for e-learning systems. Here, we describe Co-Learn and discuss the patterns' identification and formalization processes through two case studies in which a set of cognitive strategies was applied with the goal of better organizing the content seen by the student. The purpose is to facilitate the student's interaction with the material's interface and, consequently, improve the learning process.</p>]]></description>
          <pubDate>Sun, 11 Oct 2009 08:45:36 +0000</pubDate>
            </item>
